ting from tenets of modernist studies and from methods in the field of trauma and memory studies, Rizzuto contends that acute as well as chronic disruptions to imperial and national power and the legal and extra-legal responses they inspired shape the formal practices of literatures from the modernist, colonial, and postcolonial periods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCommonwealth literature (English)xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aJustice, Administration of, in literature. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglish-speaking countries. 0aNationalism and literaturezEnglish-speaking countries. 0aPsychic trauma in literature. 0aWar in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPostcolonial Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107290300 cprintz978082326781140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823267842?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823267842zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823267842/original  a978-3-11-072903-0 Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA